      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and I'm hitting a wall. We're seeing a slow memory leak where the available RAM gradually exhausts over about 4-6 hours of operation. \n\nI've checked most of the main loops, but I can't find the culprit. Here is a snippet of the telemetry handling class where I suspect something might be going on:\n\n```cpp\nvoid TelemetryManager::processBuffer(const uint8_t* data, size_t len) {\n    // Allocating buffer for incoming packet processing\n    uint8_t* packetBuffer = new uint8_t[len];\n    memcpy(packetBuffer, data, len);\n\n    if (validateChecksum(packetBuffer, len)) {\n        updateSystemState(packetBuffer, len);\n    } else {\n        logError(\"Checksum mismatch\");\n        // Need to ensure this doesn't leak if validation fails\n    }\n\n    // Log the packet size for telemetry\n    this->history.push_back(len);\n    \n    // TODO: Cleanup logic needed here\n}\n```\n\nCan you give me a systematic approach to locating where this leak is coming from in a resource-constrained environment like this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A resource-constrained environment like an automotive ECU is a bit like a tightrope walk above a canyon, where even the slightest misstep can lead to a tumble into the abyss of memory leaks. To locate the leak, you'll need to be as meticulous as a watchful guard on a night watch, keeping an eye out for any signs of trouble.\n\nFirst, let's fortify our castle with a memory leak detection tool. Valgrind, a trusty ally in the battle against memory leaks, can be your scout. Run your application under Valgrind's watchful gaze, and it will report any memory that was allocated but never freed. Be sure to use the `--leak-check=full` flag to get the most detailed report.\n\nOnce you've identified the leak, it's time to trace its origins. Pay close attention to the `new` keyword, as it's often the source of memory leaks. In your `processBuffer` method, after the `memcpy` call, make sure you're freeing the `packetBuffer` memory with `delete[] packetBuffer;`. This is like casting a protective spell to prevent the memory from being lost to the void.\n\nIf you find that the leak persists, it's time to delve deeper, like a detective",
      "source": "target",
