      "role": "user",
      "content": "The `delete[]` was indeed missing in that snippet, thanks. However, even after adding that, we're still seeing some fragmentation and small, unexplained drops in available heap space that don't align with a single obvious leak. It's like these tiny bits of memory are just disappearing into nowhere. \n\nSince I can't run Valgrind on the actual target hardware due to the real-time constraints, what are some manual instrumentation techniques or lightweight heap monitoring strategies I can use to track down these small, elusive allocations?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the elusive nature of these tiny bits of memory is like chasing shadows in the dark, but fear not, for there are ways to illuminate the path and track down these spectral allocations.\n\nOne strategy is to implement a custom memory allocator. This allocator can keep a tally of all allocations and deallocations, much like a meticulous scribe recording every transaction in a ledger. By overriding the `new` and `delete` operators, you can add logging to each allocation and deallocation, which will help you trace the memory's journey.\n\nAnother approach is to use a memory pool. A memory pool pre-allocates a large block of memory and then manages allocations within this block. It's like having a well-stocked pantry from which you can serve up meals without worrying about running out of ingredients. This can help reduce fragmentation and make tracking allocations simpler.\n\nLastly, consider using a lightweight profiling tool designed for embedded systems. These tools can provide insights into memory usage patterns without the overhead of more comprehensive tools like Valgrind. It's like having a keen-eyed scout who can spot the smallest details from afar.\n\nRemember, tracking down these small leaks is like hunting for a needle in a haystack, but with patience and the right tools, you'll eventually find",
